<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911219-0023</DOCNO><DOCID>911219-0023.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- MCI Communications Corp.:   Florida Is Expected to Give   Firm $50 Million Contract</HL><DATE>12/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   MCIC</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>LONG DISTANCE TELEPHONE PROVIDERS (LDS)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)</IN><NS>NEW PRODUCTS andamp; SERVICES (PDT)</NS><RE>DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA (DC)FLORIDA (FL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   MCI Communications Corp. said it expects to receive athree-year contract for at least $50 million from Florida toprovide a message relay system to speech and hearing-impairedresidents.   The service, which was mandated in recent statelegislation, reflects the demographics of Florida, with alarge and growing elderly population. MCI said the relaycenter, with 1,000 employees, will serve more than 1.5million of Florida's nearly 13 million residents. A spokesmanat MCI's regional office in Atlanta said the Florida PublicService Commission notified MCI of its intent to award thecontract, subject to negotiation of a final agreement within30 days.</LP><TEXT>   The contract calls for setting up a single state relaycenter to handle messages to and from speech andhearing-impaired residents. An impaired person using astate-provided computer connected to a phone line can type amessage to the phone relay center, where an operator thencalls the recipient to pass on the message. Also, twohearing-impaired people with computers can communicatedirectly.</TEXT></DOC>